-- German Stocks Extend Two-Year High; Hugo Boss Shares Advance in Frankfurt
-- B y   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 2010-10-14T16:09:50Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-14/stocks-extend-two-year-high-in-germany-fresenius-medical-hugo-boss-rise.html
German stocks climbed, extending a
two-year high, as better-than-estimated earnings boosted
confidence in the global economic recovery.  Hugo Boss AG  rallied 4.7 percent after a strong third
quarter prompted the luxury clothier to raise its earnings
forecasts. Companies from Solarworld AG to Siemens AG also
advanced.  The benchmark  DAX Index  advanced 0.3 percent to 6,455.27 in
Frankfurt, its highest close since September 2008. The gauge
rallied 2.1 percent yesterday as U.S. companies from  Intel Corp .
to JPMorgan Chase & Co. posted earnings that beat analysts’
estimates. The broader HDAX Index increased 0.3 percent today.  “Traders continue to hunt risky asset classes,” said
 Joshua Raymond , a London-based market strategist at City Index.
“Intel and JPMorgan have helped to cement gains by reporting
strong earnings this week.”  Of the 11 companies in the U.S.  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index 
to have reported results since Oct. 8, nine have beaten
analysts’ estimates for net income and revenue, according to
data compiled by Bloomberg.  Eighteen of the gauge’s companies are due to report results
this week. Analysts surveyed by Bloomberg forecast 23 percent
profit growth from a year earlier, the fourth straight quarterly
increase.  Hugo Boss  Preferred shares of Hugo Boss rallied 4.7 percent to 46.12
euros after the clothier forecast earnings before interest,
taxes, depreciation, amortization and one-time items to rise
about 20 percent for the year.  The company previously estimated growth of 10 percent to 12
percent. Hugo Boss’s third-quarter revenue increased 19 percent
to 538 million euros ($758 million), driven by the company’s own
stores and a joint venture with Chinese fashion retailer Rainbow
Group.  Solarworld AG gained 5.5 percent to 10.15 euros and SMA
Solar Technology AG climbed 4.1 percent to 85.39 euros as Piper
Jaffray’s London-based analyst,  Michael McNamara , initiated
coverage of the solar energy companies with an “overweight”
recommendation.  Siemens,  which was today upgraded to “hold” from
“underweight” at  Banco Santander SA , gained 0.9 percent to
80.50 euros.  Suedzucker AG fell 1.9 percent to 16.77 euros as the
world’s largest sugar refiner said second-quarter net income
slid to 50 million euros from 55 million euros a year earlier.  Draegerwerk AG & Co. KGaA  preferred shares lost 2.9
percent to 63.84 euros as the German maker of medical equipment
was downgraded to “underperform” from “outperform” at CA
Cheuvreux.  To contact the reporter on this story:
